``` proto
service UserService {
    rpc GetUser(GetUserRequest) returns (GetUserResponse) {}
    rpc PostUser(PostUserRequest) returns (PostUserResponse) {}
}

message GetUserRequest { string id = 1; }
message GetUserResponse { User user = 1; }

message PostUserRequest { *User* user = 1; }
message PostUserResponse { *User* user = 1; }
```

Imagine something like this with the code in asterisks having been selected by double clicking its first instance and then holding cmd and double clicking the second one.

Now press cmd-d (`find-and-replace:select-next`) repeatedly. It'll select all instances of `User` except the one in the beginning of the last line (from `PostUserResponse`). I expected it to select all instances of `User`.

I tested this using the new custom testrunner feature introduced in
https://github.com/atom/atom/pull/8968. My testrunner function was defined as follows:

``` js
'use babel';

module.exports = function({testPaths, buildAtomEnvironment, logFile, headless, legacyTestRunner}) {
  global.atom = buildAtomEnvironment();
};
```

Without this change, `buildAtomEnvironment()` threw a bunch of exceptions.
